  "prompt": "Can the sun melt snow in below freezing temperatures?",
  "response": "Yes, the sun can melt snow even when air temperatures are below freezing. This occurs through a process called solar radiation or direct solar heating. Here's how it works:\n\n1. Solar radiation can directly heat surfaces like snow, even when air temperature is below 32\u00b0F (0\u00b0C).\n\n2. Dark surfaces absorb more solar radiation and warm up faster than lighter surfaces.\n\n3. When sunlight hits snow, it can warm the snow's surface to above freezing, causing melting.\n\n4. This is why snow can melt on sunny winter days, even when the air temperature remains cold.\n\n5. The intensity of the sun, the angle of sunlight, and the snow's surface color can all affect the melting process.\n\nThis phenomenon is why you might see snow melting on dark surfaces like asphalt or rocks during winter, while the air temperature remains below freezing.",
